		   <td><font face="verdana" size="2"><P> Milo,<P>

 I enjoy your column.  Perhaps this question has been answered, but I haven't seen it.<P>

 My question is this.  There have been several posts by Gordon saying that the lack of models has something to do with the limitations of the Voodoo
1 card.  Could you explain (without getting too technical) what those limitations are?<P>

 Thanks.<P>

 Steve Lierly

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Not enough memory for more textures, too slow to process the orientation
of more polygons at an acceptable frame rate, stuff like that.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Milo Said:<P>

 "The dark elves, woodland elves, half-elves, and barbarians aren't the
only races in the game. You people need to stop pretending that they are, just
so you can complain about them being half naked. I'm going to ignore this
brand of whining, from now on."<P>

 Stacy Countered:<P>

 Hi Milo!  I never believed that starting this conversation would lead to such an interesting 'thread' so to speak.  However, I am glad it did
because it proves to me that I am not the only person who feels this way and that means that it isn't something that should be swept under the carpet or ignored.<P>

 You're right.  Not every female race is subject to this kind of 'Boris Vallejo' style of art.  However, every race that is around the same size, build and body type of your typical human female of today is.<P>

 [... yak yak yak...]<P>

 Sincerely,<BR>
 Stacy Griebel

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Bunk.  The erudite women are fully clothed.  The high elven women
are fully clothed.  The human women show a little skin, certainly not
enough to qualify them for Heavy Metal magazine.  And why aren't you
writing anything about the barbarian men, or the human male monks?<P>

   You have *so* got an agenda.  That, or you're really insecure about
your own appearance.<P>

   This message was brought to you by me -- not Verant Interactive.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 This is certainly one of the most amusing things I've seen in a while.
Some guy is employed by Verant as a game artist (or whatever), the game takes
off, and then suddenly, by some quirk of fate, he becomes the next Oprah.  He's giving love advice, witty parley, and blushing to profuse flattery.<P>

 I think I'll look into Computer Programming as a career option (not
really). I never considered it to be such a great conduit for publicity.  Milo is, indeed, the Man it would seem.<P>

 Forgive any spelling or grammarical errors.  You see, I'm a writer, and you'll find that we care even less about such things.  That's what editors (and Milo) are for.<P>

 LloyHen@aol.com

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Your jealousy would have been less obvious if you had declared
it outright.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 I'm tired of these people bitching about the way female characters look.
In real life, they get implants and liposuction to look like that..then on EQ want to be ugly.  Anyways..my question is, Does your job require good
pencil and paper drawing skills?<P>

 HbFusion@aol.com

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   No, my job doesn't require that -- although it's generally a given that a
professional artist will know how to draw.  I certainly can't think of a
single
artist at Verant Interactive (or any other software manufacturer) who can't
do it.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Hi Milo;<P>
 
 I've been wondering about something. As a champion of proper use of language, what dictionary do you prefer? Why? Any real stinkers out there (in your humble opinion)? <P>
 
 Gavin

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I use a Funk & Wagnall's pocket dictionary and a Webster's Unabridged
at home, and an American Heritage pocket dictionary at the office.  I also
keep a Roget's College Thesaurus handy, although I almost never use it.
<a href="http://www.dictionary.com/">http://www.dictionary.com/</a> is pretty good, as well.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 I had to laugh at the indignant repsonses to your dismissal of Chris's irrelevant question. What makes me laugh even harder is that the question of level-caps on dragon raids had already been dealt with and was busy provoking a new and even loader uproar on the gameplay board that week.<P>

 And yes, it is "all of whom": "all" is the subject of the subordinate clause, qualified by "of whom", which refers to the object of the main clause.<P>

 Charles<P> <P>



 Milo,<BR>
     I noticed that someone tried to correct your grammar by stating you used the word "whom" incorrectly; I found this quite entertaining. I am by no means a scholar of the English language. I, as you so eloquently put it, showed an incredible amount of disinterest when it came to education. On top of that, I am by far better with mathematics than I ever will be with the English language. With that said, I couldn't help but laugh when I saw the "correction" on the user of the word "whom" and the garble that followed. Using whom, as opposed to who, was entirely correct. I always seemed to think this was as common as knowing when to use lesser as opposed to fewer. Obviously I've been wrong. At any rate, my only real motive for posting this, besides to make someone look like a fool, was to agree with you on the point that people should at least have the decency to have a fair understanding of the language, as it reflects very badly on themselves, and generally makes communication more difficult, to not.<P>

     Also, to the person who had the audacity to state that programmers with bad grammar are lazy, you have a serious misunderstanding of a programmer(I would like to hope I do not being one myself, albeit not a incredibly knowledgeable one yet). Programming, is a form of expression that rivals all others. It requires you to learn at least one new language, though it is often more. You must master this language, to some extent, far more than any spoken language, and it is far less forgiving. I never have, nor will, find a greater outlet for my creativity and skills.<P>

 Ellegon<P> <P>



 The idiot with the argument against 'of whom are.'  You didn't rip the pompous ass up the way he so richly deserved.  When my daughter was in
high school she used to come home with questions like, "you know how you always taught me  blah blah?...Well the teacher says blah blah."  If she argued with the teacher (English was the teacher's second language for God's
sake!) the teacher threatened her grade.  So what did my daughter learn?  Power
in the face of ignorance is still power.  Did she learn any English?  Yes,
from me (not "from I").<P>

 Keep up the good work.  I have studied computer generated graphics and animation, and I am impressed with your work.  And your English.<P>

 McKay<BR>
 Fennon Ro

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Thanks for your support, gentlemen.  It's refreshing to know that
there are readers of this page out there who have a clue.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 I recently read your answer to a question concerning UO2 and was completely blown away.<P>

 I can understand you not liking the graphical style of the game, and can respect that you dont like it. That is fine. But, in all honesty, saying that "UO2 doesn't even look as good as EverQuest, in many ways" just makes me blink in confusion. Can you PLEASE tell me how EQ looks better. Even one example would please me.<P>

 The fact that you bash it's textures, "blocky" models, and non-next gen game look seems like bitterness on your behalf. EQ has huge, low res, pixelated textures(not to mention tiresome and repetitive), INCREDIBLY blocky character/monster models, and pretty lame character animation.<P>

 I'm sure you are aware that no MMORPG can ever have the quality of graphics as a single-player FPS. Afterall all, having dozens of super-smooth models and hi-res textures moving around on the screen at once would cause most up-to-date computers to chug.<P>

 For the record, bump-mapped, varied and colourful textures don't seem "non-commital" to me.

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I could very easily and very specifically name several ways in which
EQ has better graphics, but unfortunately, the intolerance of some game
players and industry "professionals" has made it bad business for me to
speak or write negatively of the game any further.  In light of this, I have
been commanded to maintain critical silence.  You will likely have to
wait until you meet someone who has heard my reasons for writing what
I wrote about the Ultima Online sequel.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 I have been with EQ on the Povar server since shortly after it's release
to the public.  While everyone seems to have his/her own version of the
"Perfect Game", I have found that Verant has done a damn good job of creating a thoroughly immersive environment with awesome graphics, superb character animations and models, and the best in-game support staff of all the
online games out there that I have played to date.  Having jumped the sinking
ship of the forerunner to the game you are no longer allowed to discuss due to threats to your manhood and personal wealth, and having also viewed the unmentionable pile of pixelated trash that is to be the graphics for said "unmentionable" product...I can only agree with your views.  I am sure as soon as it is released, all "da pimp masta sword butt stallionz" as they
call their online personas by name, that do their best to ruin all online games (but seem to live in larger numbers in said competitors online world, especially after in game support turns the lights off) with their moronic speech and actions, will no doubt also complain what trash it is, and pray that {insert competitor's parent company name and logo here} sends a team
of commandos to forcibly procure Rick Schmitz and yourself, to turn it into something worth looking at.  Having spouted off for the last 40 paragraphs without actually making some kind of point...I leave it at this. YOU ROCK!<BR>
 Now for my Questions...<P>

 1.)  Having read through some of the emails sent to you, I have to
ask...Do the veins in your head ever threaten to pop out and explode from the sheer volume of morons out there?  Furthermore, Do you condone choking people
that obviously appear to need it?<P>

 2.)  If a troll was running backwards at the speed of light, and it
scratched it's big flea bitten arse would it explode? (I'm sorry...I really am,
having read some of the posts sent to you has really warped my mind, or as they would've spelled it "wrapped my monded.")  8-)~<P>

 PS  Keep being yourself, you sound like a man after my own heart.  I get accused of being mean natured all the time, simply because my tolerance
level for stupidity and ignorance have been decreased over the last 29 years,
(as have my grammar skills no doubt) and sometimes you just have to say what's
on your mind, and have to do it the "nicest" way possible...and it is SooooOOOooooOo hard not to add in those hidden slams that I have
ROFLMAO'ed over as I caught them hidden but in such plain sight in your replies. Oh
what a world this would be if there was a minimum IQ level to be allowed to breathe.<P>

 Yours truly,<BR>
 Grimcleaver "da ugliest butt scratchinest troll warrior on Povar"

