<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

    What modelers in the video game industry do you currently look up to, or respect for the work they've done on recent products? I thought the work on Quake 2, EverQuest, MDK2 and Bungie's upcoming game Halo are all excellent examples; they gave the models a personality and lifelike quality animation that very few other games can even come close to, and made those respective games that much more enjoyable to play. Anyway, would love to hear who you think does good work in your area of expertise.<P>

 Yander

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Namco's Soul Calibur has very sweet character models.  Lots of polygons,
anatomically detailed, motion-captured movement, and wonderful hair and
clothing physics.  Imagine a MMORPG with graphics like that!  The next
Metal Gear game, developed for PlayStation 2, looks spectacular as well.<P>

   Actually, though, I think that it would be really neat to work on a 2D
game.
I love what Capcom's artists have done with their post-Street Fighter II
Super Turbo games; when I first saw Darkstalkers, I felt as though I was
actually watching an anime cartoon.  The graphics in Capcom's fighting
games are very vibrant and very exaggerated, just the kind of stuff I like
to
create.  Working on something like that would be a blast, and a nice change
of pace for me.  Oh, well!<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Milo,<P>

     First let me say that I love your models.  My character is a Wood Elf so when I'm fighting the Orcs in Highpass Pass, I have to tilt the "camera" up so I can see them.  I simply enjoy that I am fighting something that is a lot bigger than I am.  The sizes of the different creatures is amazing.  My hat is off to you.  Please pass on to the respective people, that the character animation and texture art are extrememly well done.  I love them too.  =)<P>

 My questions:<BR>
 1) Can you divuldge what software you use?  (Lightwave 3D, 3D Studio, etc.)<BR>
 2) Did you have any inspiration for your models like a movie or comic book or TV show?<BR>
 3) Do you have a bachelor's or master's degree in computer graphic art? If not, did you teach yourself?<P>
 
 Thanks in advance,<P>
 
 Rob

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I'm asked these questions all the time.  I think I'm going to put an Ask
Milo FAQ on my web site, since people don't seem to want to use the
archives, here.<P>

   I use Maya and 3D Studio MAX (mostly).  My main inspirations are
the comic book art of Mike Mignola, Rick Schmitz's character designs,
and music in general.  I have had no formal training (beyond a few brief
classes on the use of Maya and PowerAnimator) in the field of computer
graphics -- so yes, I am self-taught.<P>

   I'm sure that Rick Schmitz (animator) and Rick Johnson (textures)
appreciate your compliments about their work.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Dear Milo,<BR>
     I would first like to congradulate you and thank you for taking our questions!  Personally, I think I play the game too much, and I think I'm
not the only one. =P<P>

 When you were a kid what did you want to be when you grew up? Being that
I'm still a kid, I have a lot of dreams.  The rest of what I wanted to say was pretty much covered already.<P>

 Sincerely,<BR>
         Phil

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   As I child, I developed several ambitions.  Doctor, composer, writer,
husband
and father, architect, comic book artist, programmer, grandmaster chess
player,
film director, superhero... but never a computer graphics artist!  With the
exception of composer, I've given up on all of those things; life has pretty
much
narrowed it all down, for me.<P>

